The White House Press Secretary, Robert Gibbs, held a briefing on March 30, 2009. During the briefing, Gibbs discussed the government's involvement in the auto industry and the recent management changes at GM and Chrysler. He emphasized that the government is not running these companies but is taking measures to protect taxpayers and seek the best solution for the long-term viability of the companies. Gibbs also addressed questions about warranties and the government's role in backing them. He mentioned that he would double-check the specifics of the warranty issue. Additionally, Gibbs responded to questions about the differences in the government's approach to the auto industry compared to the banking industry. He emphasized the administration's commitment to transparency and accountability in the use of taxpayer money. The briefing also touched on other topics such as the signing of the omnibus land bill and the legality of using TARP funds for the auto bailout.